XPO Logistics (XPO): Remarkable Growth in A Mature Industry


June 03, 2015, 01:14:41 PM EDT
By Martin Tillier









































Shutterstock photo


For corporations, growth comes in many forms. Some companies, such as Google (GOOG, GOOGL) become dominant forces in industries that are destined for growth and their expansion is largely a function of the growth of the industry. Some, such as Amazon (AMZN), pursue growth at the expense of short-term profits, ruthlessly eliminating competitors to dominate an existing industry. In both of those cases, though, sector-wide growth is a contributing factor to the ultimate success of the strategy. Achieving exponential growth in a mature industry is significantly more difficult.There are some well-known examples, but usually they involve disruption of an accepted business model or a change in the basic product. Tesla (TSLA) would be a good example of that. Occasionally, you come across a company that achieves remarkable growth in a mature industry by simply being better than the competition and making smart decisions about expansion and acquisition. XPO Logistics (XPO) is one such company.XPO is a Greenwich, Connecticut based transportation logistics company. Their growth has been truly remarkable so far, from $158 million in revenue in 2010 to $2.46 billion last year, but according to CEO and Chairman Bradley Jacobs, that is just the beginning. In a statement on Monday detailing a $3.26 billion mixed equity and debt issue to raise capital, Jacobs described the company’s growth strategy as “...still in its early innings.” Given the performance over the last few years and analysts’ projections of 40 percent growth in the next year, those are scary words for the freight forwarding industry.When companies raise capital it is often a warning sign for investors. If, as in the case of many small oil exploration and production companies this year, it is to tide them through tough times. An equity issue can seriously dilute the existing stock, while issuing new debt adds to ongoing expenses. The fact that this news barely registered as a blip on XPO’s chart this week, then, indicates that investors have remarkable confidence in Jacobs and his team.That confidence is understandable, and fairly easily explained. Firstly, it doesn’t come as a surprise. XPO have announced two major acquisitions in the last few months. At the end of April they released plans to buy Norbert Dentressangle S.A. and then just a few days later revealed that they would be acquiring Bridge Terminal Transport Services, Inc. Incidentally, the scope and potential of the Dentressangle deal may be lost on many Americans, but as a European I am only too aware of the ubiquity of that company’s trucks on the other side of the pond.However, takeovers like that need capital, so news of new equity and debt was expected. It is a measure of confidence in the company that all of that new stock was purchased by existing shareholders and that Moody’s gave the new debt issue a B1 rating. In part, that is down to the track record of the CEO. Jacobs was the founder of United Waste Systems and co-founder of United Rentals, both of which adopted aggressive, but ultimately very successful growth by acquisition strategies. He clearly knows what he is doing here, a belief that is further evidenced by the timing of the deal. It took advantage of dollar strength before the exchange rate began to turn, adding value almost instantly.Sooner or later, of course, even the most aggressive growth company has to make money to make it all worthwhile, but if most estimates are to be believed that shouldn’t pose a problem for XPO. They are generally expected to move to profit later this year and the fact that a large part of the capital scheduled to be raised from the latest offering is to bolster the acquisition fund indicates that profitability can be maintained while still pursuing yet more growth in the future.For a growth strategy to be attractive to investors, one of two requirements must be met. It must have proven to be effective in the past, and there must be confidence in the ability of the management team to handle the rapid expansion. XPO meets both of those requirements, so, despite the stock doubling in the last year, the best may yet be to come.



The views and opinions expressed herein are the views and opinions of the author and do not necessarily reflect those of Nasdaq, Inc.











